                    bottom Ramaphosa vows power transfer to be finalised Deputy president Cyril Ramaphosa says ANC NEC members, who are set to meet on Monday, will finalise a power transition from President Jacob Zuma. Ramaphosa said he understands South Africans want the country's leadership to resolve its problems and that the national executive committee (NEC) "will be doing precisely that". #Mandela100 heralds new beginning for SA, says hopeful Ramaphosa “As we emerge from a period of difficulty, a period of disunity and discord, this Nelson Mandela centenary year offers us what I would call, a new beginning,” says Deputy President Cyril Ramaphosa. He was addressing a crowd at the Grand Parade in Cape Town on Sunday, where the ANC held a rally to mark Nelson Mandela’s centenary. “This year we are called upon, all of us, to look at where we have come from and to look at our weaknesses, to look at the challenges we face,” Ramaphosa said. “As we emerge from a period of difficulty, a period of disunity and discord, this Nelson Mandela centenary year offers us what I would call, a new beginning.” #Ramaphosa: "Let us make our country the country of our dreams. Long live the spirit of Nelson Mandela, long live," he finishes to applause. #Mandela100 @TeamNews24 pic.twitter.com/pJ1Jlf1srm #Ramaphosa: Let us all focus our attention on embracing the values and principles that Nelson Mandela had embraced; ridding of our country of corruption, theft and all the negative things. #Mandela100 @TeamNews24 pic.twitter.com/Y6d84fSVgd Ramaphosa gives strongest indication yet that ANC was not successful in negotiating a graceful exit deal with Zuma and that the NEC will recall him tomorrow. @TeamNews24 #Mandela100 Army officials continue to oversee #Ramaphosa's #Mandela100 speech from above. @TeamNews24 pic.twitter.com/BllDNk3Caj #Ramaphosa confirms the ANC NEC will be finalising the #ZumaExit talks tomorrow. It will all come to an end. Huge applause. "We know you want closure." #Ma